Class Event

  • java.lang.Object
    • src.Event

  • public class Event
extends java.lang.Object
    Activity to be scheduled and deployed during the application execution. An event is an action -like stand up or walk- that takes place in a certain time, with details attached to it like description, duration and period. Event objective is to reduce or avoid health issues related to long periods of computing use.

    • Field Detail

      • title

        java.lang.String title
        Title of the event, short and accurate.

      • description

        java.lang.String description
        Detailed description of the event.

      • period

        int period
        Time -in seconds- it takes to repeat the event.

      • duration

        int duration
        Duration -in seconds- of the event.

      • timeToLaunch

        int timeToLaunch
        Remaining time -in seconds- until event starts. This variable is used to control the execution of the events (when it reaches 0, it means that the event has fulfilled another iteration of its period, and must be launched).

      • startingTime

        boolean startingTime
        Establishes if the event shall be executed only at a certain time. If 'true', event period is 24 hours, meaning that it only fires once each 24 hours.

      • startingHour

        int startingHour
        Decomposition of the 'startingTime' in hours, minutes and seconds. Decomposition in 24 hour digital format. Minimal value is 0:0:0 and maximun is 23:59:59.

      • startingMinute

        int startingMinute
        Decomposition of the 'startingTime' in hours, minutes and seconds. Decomposition in 24 hour digital format. Minimal value is 0:0:0 and maximun is 23:59:59.

      • startingSecond

        int startingSecond
        Decomposition of the 'startingTime' in hours, minutes and seconds. Decomposition in 24 hour digital format. Minimal value is 0:0:0 and maximun is 23:59:59.

    • Method Detail

      • decreaseTTL

        public void decreaseTTL()
        Decreases TimeToLaunch (TTL) value in one unit. TimeToLaunch represents the number of seconds until the event shall be fired. This method decreases its value in one unit, simulating the pass of one second.

      • restartTimeToLaunch

        public void restartTimeToLaunch()
        Restarts 'timeToLaunch' to its initial value, equal to event's period. 'timeToLaunch' value get restarted each time it reachs 0 value (thats it, each time the event is fired, meaning another period iteration has been fullfiled).
